title: TronXY X3A Linear Rail Guide Mount

description.text:
This is a Linear Rail mount for the TronXY X3...

I think they can be used on any machine that has 2020 extrusion.. But have not tested this.

These mounts make clearance for the bed to be able to reach its max Y distance.

Linear Rail Guide/Mount for any 2020 Extrusion - Short Version

Do not put too much tension on the bolt and nut when tightening the rail in the holder. It is very strong but i have had a few lower %infill ones break on me. : P

These make clearance with most linear rail upgrades, if not all, for the TronXY X3 or other printers.

These also make clearance with most Y-Axis tensioners as the reason for re-design was two fold.

  1. To shorten mounts and clear bed now on linear rails to allow for max print area.
  2. Shorten width-wise to make clearance for beautifully designed Axis tensioners.

Make sure your tensioner will fit though... some are wider than the ones i've seen/tested.

3dBuilder - Split then merged in place of desire. Measured heights and slits to recreate the tensioning but under the rail rather than on top.

Thank you AdaFruit for the original design.

description.text:
The Stingray Cruiser has been my printed quad project this summer. The goal was to create a minimal FPV cruiser quad, integrating a stabilized GoPro mount with a large and stable platform. The frame is capable of swinging up to 10" props and probably larger if you wanted. It is photographed with 8" props, which offer great acro response. The flight controller is center mounted with ESCs routed through the arms. The octagonal arm form and integrated push fitting makes for quite a strong quad. The profile is a slightly stretched-X style.

Components used in the build–

-spool of PC-Max (white)
-Betaflight F3 flight controller
-Emax Bullet 35A ESCs
-HobbyKing NTM 2826 1200kv short shaft motors
-Runcam Swift 2 camera with 2.1 IR block lens
-Matek Systems HUBOSD8-SE PDB
-Foxeer antenna
-Foxeer 600mw VTX
-Panasonic aluminum cap 470UF 20% 35V radial capacitors on each ESC
-4-6 cell battery, 1300-2700mah (can run multiple packs in parallel with double battery strap)
-dampening plate–
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00VFYIFFM/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
-GoPro Session mount (I use this on almost all of my quads)–
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2044443
-26mm standoffs
-40mm m3 socket head screws
-m3 washers and locknuts

I definitely took inspiration from a few other frames listed on Thingiverse, which is why I am returning this frame design to the printing community. The frame isn't perfect but I think it does a few things very well. Please post your results if you decide to take it on. Cheers!

UPDATE (07/26/17) – Open field flying on 6s yields impressive results. I don't care for these motors though, they omit a good amount of vibration. It won't be long before the bearings start having issues. I have a set of Sunnysky motors that will hopefully make their way onto the frame at some point. The PIDS are a little sloppy, which can tighten up with a bit of tuning. Enjoy!

title: REMIXED: Ol' Soft Shoe for Kossel Delta
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This thing is a remix of the Ol' Soft Shoe (Vibration Dampening) by Thingiverse user HauntFreaks.

I think that is a brilliant design, but it doesn't work well for delta-style printers constructed from 2020 aluminum extrusion, and with the angled connectors on a Delta printer, it won't allow you to put the foot in a maximally stable position. I added feet at a 60 degree angle to position the foot outboard and squarely under the uprights of a Kossel Delta 3Dprinter. The mounting holes are dimensioned to accept M4 fasteners and captive nuts in the channels of the 2020.

NOTE: I bought a couple of batches of foam practice golf balls for this application and discovered that foam practice balls vary in absolute and relative firmness. You want the least squishy golf balls you can find. I recommend going to a sporting goods store and assessing them in person, rather than buying them online. In the Seattle area, we have Big5, and they had about six different products. Once you find the firmest option, you want to select three balls that are equally firm. My first attempt resulted in one very soft ball and a leaning printer. So many jokes in this paragraph, and you have been warned.

description.text:
Tuggers are a cable strain relief gadget that has a number of uses but the main one is in protecting sockets from being damaged when a cable is accidentally ripped out.

This is a remix of my original design with a change to the cord entry into a more reliable 'peg' style entry and apart from that I've tweaked and improved it all around for strength and function.

Twice now I’ve had my camera monitor fall off the hot shoe adapter. Once was after a bit of camera movement but the second was when I accidentally hooked the HDMI cable and yanked it off. I’m not too concerned about the monitor but both times it ripped out the micro HDMI plug on my Sony with some considerable force. Fortunately the HDMI socket on my camera handled the extreme handling without causing any permanent damage.

I tried Jerkstoppers but they were a pain to use... that's when I decided to build a better cable strain relief and I came up with my design called Tuggers.

I've put together a short youtube video showcasing the original designs and although a bit different the overall concept is the same so well worth a watch:-
https://youtu.be/sWLgZHM7_Ro

There's 3 Sizes:-

The Lil' Tugger is for protecting sockets by attaching to cables sized around hdmi or USB cables.

The Regular Tugger is for protecting sockets by attaching it to cables sized around mains cable or up to a couple of HDMI or USB cables.

The Big Tugger is for protecting power sockets by attaching it to cables sized around large mains cables or multiple cables.

description.text: Unside down gazebo

Bracket to repair a broken refrigerator handle on a Frigidaire LFHT1817LW3. This is for the fridge handle, not the freezer handle. Requires cutting off an exact amount of the handle due to the spacers inside the cap part. Improves original design as it's thicker and has a hook to reach the far side in addition to the screws.

From the top of the fridge door down to the top of the cut off fridge handle, that vertical distance needs to be 14.44 mm. At that distance, the handle will be fully seated in the cap, the bracket flush with the top of the fridge door, and the factory bottom mounting screw pulled up into the handle slot.

The bracket isn't perfect, the rotation of the handle profile is off a little so when installed, it's slightly twisted, but still works. The cap is also a very very tight fit on the handle, you may need to chamfer the edges of the handle and scrape bracket/handle as needed. I went with the very tight over a loose fit so the handle doesn't fall off since there's no fasteners on the bracket apart from the two screws used to hold it to the door on the top.

Can print at any infill percentage, more is probably better, all the way to solid. Print with supports for counterbore holes as they're upside-down. Solidworks 2008 file included.

title: Schlaboratory ATX Power Supply Shroud
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I really like using an ATX power supply for the 3Dprinters I build. Even though they come in a variety of wattages and supply abundant 12-volt happiness, they have a bunch of other wiring harnesses attached. You COULD snip or unsolder the unnecessary wiring, but opening the case will certainly invalidate your warranty, and maybe some day you will wish you hadn't. You could just zip-tie the wires out of the way, but that looks rather unpolished (and poses other mechanical/electrical hazards).

This free-standing shroud tidies up your wiring, allows you to keep your PSU intact, and preserves your warranty. The shroud is designed to hold the PSU captive from opposite corners and not block the ventilation. The PSU is oriented vertically to minimize the footprint. There is a hole in the cavity to run a 12V power cable to the printer through a grommet.

The PSU I used has some nifty sheathing on the various harnesses, which adds some bulk to the wiring, but it all fits nicely in the arched cavity. I folded and zip-tied each harness separately, which allowed me to arrange the wires a little easier. I made an assumption about the position of the cooling fan on my PSU, which looks silly, but I have enlarged the cut-out to accommodate some variation in ventilation design.

05-Sep: Finally all the parts have been printed and fits smoothly on 2020 profile. Original desing by Scott for Z nut holder fits fine also.
18-Sep: Idlers for 10mm rod. Modified Y endstop bracket to fit better with endstop flag. New Extruder mount to fit both min and max opto endstop. Files for 8mm Z rods.
13-Dec: Well, after a long time I finished the printer a coule of weeks ago. New pictures are available in order to check the whole remix from the original HEVO.
I added a TFT32 controller + MKS WiFi module. Also, in the same enclosure I added a couple o LED to indicate when either E0 or the Heatedbed are working. All the desings for the parts I'm using are available for download.
Also I attached two led stripes that can be turned on from MKSTFT32 and a runout filament sensor to help avoiding run out of filament during long printings.
It's fair to mention I remixed the spool holder from @bliatun (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2084843) and @rowokii (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:767317).
19-Jan: Redesigned Extruder Mount. The problem I found with the original version is that the brass knurled inserts are not attached strongly enough to the plastic, so once you start tigthening the bolts, the inserts start poping out. In this new design, the inserts were placed at the back of the piece, so you can tight the screws as much as you want with out any issue.

description.text:
A basic Mini Skewb that I made a long time ago, with the intention of using it for various shape mods. It measures 35mm to an edge. It requires four Dayan screws and springs to function; these can be purchased on TheCubicle.us. The pictures show a possible sticker pattern that is more interesting than a standard 6-color Skewb.

Some notes:

  • Two core files are included; they have slightly different tolerances to account for different expansion/contraction in ABS and PLA.
  • Two center files are included; the one with an alignment nub can be used to more easily attach custom extensions.
  • The "floating corner" is constructed of a stem and base which are tightly fit together when printed in ABS. It may be slightly loose when printed in PLA and may need to be glued.
  • Caps need to be attached with a dab of glue. There is not enough surface area for the cap to stay gripped on by itself.

remixed_from.author: Reflector
remixed_from.title: Wanhao Duplicator 6 Offset Fan Direct Cooling Duct ("The Magnum")

description.text:
Low sarcasm, low humor and boring summary ahead.

Edit: Added a photo (Third in sequence) for anyone asking "will it airprint." 215C @ 0.3mm height, fairly slow rate at 12mm/s since I had to low the temperature on that print and I manually sped to prevent underextrusion given I'm pushing so much filament through. Been printing with this nozzle at 240C and it holds up.

Fits a 40x40x20mm centrifugal blower (Go on Amazon/ebay/whatever and you'll probably recognize what I got, the connector is a JST XHP-2. Remember, 24V or the fan motor will suffer). The greater Z depth of the fan, centrifugal blower instead of an axial fan, etc means you get more static pressure. Helps with these shrouds since they're not nice big clean funnels that point right at the nozzle and are instead rings. You will experience significantly improved airflow with this design and with a blower. That is according to my hand anyways. The Supermagnum did pretty well in regards to bridging already but I'm not stopping there when I have options to make something even better.

Holes are left in on the plate to allow you to use the screw and nuts of your choice to secure the adapter plate onto the Supermagnum. If your prints are messy and have a little bit of material in the hole causing them to be semi undersized, then you can possibly get away without a nut on the end of the screw, right up until you strip the tiny pieces of ooze out anyways. You now know why I left in the two "unneeded" holes on my designs. Modularity and room for growth is pretty useful.

The shroud is effectively the same as the Supermagnum but with the cavity modified to fit a perpendicular axial blower in that kind of a compact arrangement. To fit the blower flat with the housing with the intake pointed up would take some redesign time and I just wanted to have an already designed, tested and proven shroud without having to go through a dance and basically have a functional design out the day I got the centrifugal blower. The only problem is that it does tend to bump into the belt if you travel right up to the very front of the build area, so you will lose a tiny little bit of build area, mostly to the tension spring on the belt since that will actually catch right up on the fan housing.

When replacing the fan, the connectors are on the left. On my D6, it appears to be the connector on the front. There's a little bit of hot melt on but it appears to not add significant holding force to the connector. There is also possibly a connector that bridges the board to the extruder that will be over the connectors, pulling the end out on the motor will make your life easier. I recommend cutting the ziptie after you print this and if you have to use a cutting instrument that could nick the wires, to have the wires arranged in such a way you're more likely to take out the fan you're trying to replace rather than any of the other wires.

Also regarding the bracket: I am pretty sure the little mount I put in for the screw on the blower is all kinds of not accurately placed given I've went through several revisions and the current one released is actually untested due to me making some last minute changes to pull the bracket a little closer to the screw mount. Otherwise the dimensions for the rectangular hole for the blower and all the other mounting holes I know work. Right now I just tape the fan from the bottom of the bracket and into the inside of the exhaust of the fan. This helps with sealing it to the bracket and by extension, the duct. It seems to hold fine for now and I will probably be making revisions to the bracket but if you want to try to get it now then the stls are here for you.

Also if you are wondering why the blower is orientated like that: It has plain bearings, so I am sure the bearings in it feel happier that way than lying down and dealing with some thrust loading. And no, inverting it doesn't help since it causes the same problem as the original fan and duct mount: It ends up pulling air from too close to the HOT BED. This means a redesign to lower the fan will be more nuanced since it needs to have the advantages of increased blow while having the large diameter of the Supermagnum, etc. Which means I will effectively be making a completely new duct instead of a variant of a reliable design.

A warning: You will lose a little bit of print area in the rear left corner (Perspective: You facing the printer) if you use these ducts, they will bump the motor. They effectively take about 1 inch/2-3cm, as in the legs of a triangle more or less. Obviously you have more to lose if you stick anything like a heatsink onto your steppers. Also you will lose a small (About 1 inch/2-3cm) strip that is about 1/4"/5mm in the front center due to the belt tensioning clip bumping into the blower. Unless you like that kind of centrifugal blower fan on belt tensioning clip action, I recommend not to drag the models dead center to the front.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Duplicator 6

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

You're not going to have a fun time bridging this unless you already printed a Supermagnum since the modified cavity doesn't have any bridging assists, nor can I really put much in there since that wouldn't be helpful to the airflow, unless I am actually doing something to redirect it into the ring, which is why this is a prototype and a work in progress.

See the Supermagnum if you need print information, this is pretty much more of the same, but with the extra difficulty of bridging the cavity on the duct. You may want to consider printing it upside down and just cleaning the supports off the bracket.

description.text:
A new type of quick-release clamp designed to slide and lock on aluminum t-slot extrusion. With this fully printable model you can build bar clamps of arbitrary size and mount multiple clamps on the same bar.

Minimalist/functional by design: only two parts, both print without supports and assembles like a puzzle.

The cam-lock lever mechanism is designed such that it puts slight pressure in the jaws when it locks and releases quickly with a snap then slides freely, making part switching effortless compared to classic vise/screw models.

The model is fully parametric via Customizer or OpenSCAD: not only you can control the size of the clamps and their features (grooves and such) but also fit these on the most common aluminum extrusions:

  • Misumi 15mm/20mm (1515 or 2020)
  • OpenBeam
  • 80/20 1010 1"
  • MicroRax 10mm
  • ... or even your own T-Slot or C-section profile.

A few video examples: https://youtu.be/aWFwbUx84aI https://youtu.be/W1OkOy_swrU

description.text:
This is revision 4 of a Monoprice Ultimate (Wanhao D6) vent plate. It uses a 4020 blower fan to blow air directly on plastics to help with print quality and bridging. The concept behind this design is to reduce sagging, decrease footprint and increase stability. There is an increase of 10mm on the right side of the mounting holes. Take this into account if building models that require more build plate surface.

https://youtu.be/pLqsar4VC5M

To assemble and attach the blower you will need.

  1. [email protected] 4020 24v blower fan (may need to extend wires)
  2. [email protected] M3x18mm hex bolts
  3. [email protected] M3 hex nuts

The mounting holes are a tight fit. Hex nuts will need to be press fit into place. First install the hex nuts. Attach the vent plate to the heatsink. Lastly attach the blower motor to the mount.

I have also included my bridge test STL which tests the vent plate at 25mm/50mm/75mm distances. at 25mm sag is nearly unnoticeable. At 50mm very slight. 75mm more noticable but still bridges very well. The included video shows PLA printing at 65mm/s. Slower speed may yield better results.

NOTE: The included photos are of the final test print using PLA. I would highly recommend ABS if able.

description.text:
These are X and Y endstop mounts for the Biqu Laser Engraver.

SAFETY NOTE!!!
Lasers are nothing to mess with. Please, please, please....wear your goggles EVERY TIME YOU ARE RUNNING THE LASER! Anything above 500mW is considered Class 4. Even the briefest of flashes can permanently cause eye damage or blindness. You only have one set of eyes.

This thing is incredibly bright while lasing, even from a distance. Keeps your kids away, lock the door to prevent someone walking in and post a sign letting people know you're running a laser.

Safety rant over...

The laser engraver I bought is sold by Biqu, but is pretty much the same as any "LaserAxe" unit. Mine happens to have the 7000 mW laser head, but the frame style and control boards are all the same.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0716WJ96L/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Since it's running GRBL, and it has the connections on the board for it, I added endstops to be able to run the homing routine. Just simple mechanical lever switches, wired up Normally Open.

Yes, the way they are mounted makes 0,0 in the upper right of the machine. This is normal for most CNC machines.

I am using both T2 Laser and Laser Web v4 to run the machine.

T2 Laser comes with a customized version of GRBL for the LaserAxe control boards. It seems they use a slightly different pinout. I'm running GRBL 1.1f. I set parameter $27 (Homing pull-off) = 2.000. But you may need more depending on your switch.

The X endstop mounts to the rear plate for the gantry using the lower roller bolts. The Y endstop mounts to the extrusion using standard drop in nuts and 3mm bolts.

The mounts both have a 1mm hole for the switches. I drilled them out to 2mm and just screwed in my screws. No nuts. But you should check your mounting dimension to verify your switches will line up.

I printed these in PETG, but pretty sure you could use whatever filament you like.

title: E3D Cyclops adapter for FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text:
This is a direct-drive adapter that will fit the FlashForge Creator Pro printer with the E3D Cyclops extruder.

WARNING: Do not perform this upgrade on your primary or sole 3D printer. It is difficult to undo. This upgrade is done AT YOUR OWN RISK.

I got mine here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01JVTUDSY
IMPORTANT: Ask for the 24v version - read the tiny print.

I can confirm that this extruder will work with the Creator Pro, but requires a lot of maintenance. Material mixing technology is still very experimental and that includes the Cyclops.

Expect a lot of clogs and cleaning.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

100%

Notes:

IMPORTANT: Infill density should be set to 100%

I printed this using HatchBox ABS: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00J0H8EWA

Extruder Temp: 210
Bed Temp: 70
Brim: 5mm, 2 layer

Step 1

Print the adapter. Clean off the brim (if used) and break off the support under the center fan screw holes.

Step 2:

Disassemble the printer carriage keeping the feeders, thermocouples, fans, heating modules and all screws.

Insert two of the smallest screws into the bottom-inner screw holes as shown below.

Step 3

Remove the right thermocouple from its threaded casing. I did this by heating it to a very high temp with a soldering iron. The thermocouple should come out when the glue holding it loosens.

NOTE: If the existing thermocouples are worn & used like mine you can get a new one: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00QKQ8G0E

Once removed from its casing replace the thermalresistor that came with the Cyclops. You wont need this and it can be discarded.

You can tie-off and retract the left thermocouple into the printer's casing if you want but you must leave it connected.

Step 4

Remove the left heating module completely from your system (you will need to open the bottom of your printer for this. Its wires are screwed onto the board and are easy to remove.

Clip the wires of the right heating module at the component end so you can connect them to the heating module of the Cyclops.

IMPORTANT: When ordering the Cyclops you MUST specify the 24v version. If, like me, you did not read this tiny bit of print you can order a compatible module (and a few spares) here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00SUYVLYC

When you've done this connect the Cyclops heating module. I used and recommend using wire nuts for this. Make sure you make the connection a good distance from the actual extruder.

Step 5

Clip two lengths of PTFE tubing. Your goal is these will sit flush with the top of the feeding pathway and extend all the way down into the Cyclops left & right chambers.

NOTE: Remove the bowden fittings from the top of the Cyclops. You will not need these.

Step 6

Connect the Cyclops to the adapter (feeding the PTFE tubing into the left/right chambers) using two of the long screws from the previous carriage assembly.

NOTE: Remove the bowden fittings from the top of the Cyclops. You will not need these.

Step 7

Mount the left/right feeders onto the adapter. The 2 screw heads you inserted into the feeders earlier should fit snug into recesses in the adapter. Use two of the medium screws from the original carriage assembly to secure the feeders in the outside screw holes.

Step 8

Attach the right fan and heatsync to the adapter as shown below.

I used screws here that measured about 3.35mm in diameter. They came from here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00CR8ZRC4

NOTE: You can remove and discard the left fan. It won't be needed.

At this point I recommend using zip-ties to secure all your wires and a couple of ties at the bottom of the adapter feet to ensure it doesn't split. I have provided an extrusion at the top of the adapter for securing things down up there.

Step 9

Attach the entire assembly to the carriage base from the previous assembly as shown below.

I used screws here that measured about 3.35mm in diameter. They came from here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00CR8ZRC4

That's it! You're ready to try this out!

Guidelines
  • Always keep two filaments loaded - even if you are only printing with 1
  • Always use filaments with similar print settings & tolerances
  • Favor low retraction settings
  • Do not use retraction when changing tools
  • Feed both filaments for a bit using the system tools before each print
Usage

Right-Side Only

Remember that this is a multi-feed, single extruder now. Your machine still thinks there are two individual extruders. I get around this by always setting my left filament heat to something low like 15 degrees and rely on my right heater and thermocouple to do all the heating work.

Avoid settings that wait for your left extruder to cool or stabilize.

Be super careful with retraction. There are open pathways between both materials now. You have to make sure material is loaded in both feeds to keep the other from backfilling molten plastic into it. This is going to be a huge source of clogs.

Material Mixing

Keep in mind that when switching tools now you have to always bleed the previous material out. Use a large prime pillar for this.

As software progresses there will be more options to actually use the mixing to create gradients. Currently I am unaware of any software that will provide this functionality for this upgrade.

More to come!

As I experiment more with this I will post new things that I find here.

Cheers!

This adapter is specifically to mount the Nimble on the new PCB effector that Escher3D is developing with Think3dPrint3d. It uses a new hot end mount that is developed by E3D.
Have a look at the new effector [here.]
(https://duet3d.com/wiki/Smart_effector_and_carriage_adapters_for_delta_printer)

Simply bolt the adapter to the hot end mount and bolt the Nimble to the adapter.

In case your printer is in pieces, or you want perfect precision, you can also get this adapter via Shapeways.

Edit 1:

Added Version 2 to the models. The method of attaching the Hot end to the PCB effector has changed, so the mounting method of the adapter needs to change. It is now done with 6.6 mm standoffs. The adapter has 3 holes for M2.5 and the PCB has 3 2.9 mm holes.
The adapter fits on top of the hot end and has a 5 mm deep hole in the bottom for the PTFE tube.
This way you clamp the PTFE tube into the hot end when you bolt the adapter down.
Alternate model has 3 integrated legs to make it easier to mount. Will be a bit more difficult to print, though.

Edit 2:

Added a little pipe holder for use with a Berd-Air like part cooling system.
It is slightly off center to allow the LED in the corner to still shed some light on the printed parts. It uses the Magnetic ball bolts to clamp it to the PCB and has a little rest for the tubing. You can use a tie-wrap to clamp the tubing to the rest.

Edit 3:

The standoff of 6.6 mm was not enough, needed to be 7.6 mm.
So changed the files to reflect this and you now need version V2.1 is you want the integrated legs.

Edit 4:

Added version V2.2. The only difference is that the leg closest to the 6 wire black plug is lowered to be below the latch or clip of the plug. Thus making it easier to unlatch and less prone to breaking. For now only the STL as the real fix (turn the plug around) is easy to implement and will be probably changed in future versions of the Smart Effector.

Edit 5:

Added version V2.4. I followed DJDemonD's suggestion and added a 12 sided hole in the bottom to lock the hot end mounting nut in place. Here is DJ's mount: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2740387
Also added a split version, with Top and Bottom half, so it can be printed and then glued together. You will need to add a little support under one of the bolt holes.
I didn't the Step files for that, as it is too easy to make that yourself.

The Nimble Extruder

With an installed weight of less than 27 grams on your carriage/effector the Zesty Nimble is smallest and lightest extruder you can buy, it has ample torque and can be mounted in multiple orientations.

The Nimble is available from Zesty Technology.

description.text:
update: first test drive:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lIAApFmTO7k

Holding up well :D

I reinforced the tracks by making them slightly thicker and added some grooves and printable profiles. The profiles have two small cutouts, which I needed to compensate for some filament blobs that appear there on the grooves in the chain links. YMMV.

I printed my profiles in flexpla, which seems to help a lot with traction on smooth surfaces. To glue them to the PLA tracks, I tried various glues, including epoxy, CA and others. Loctite Gel Control works very well, but a €8 tube only had enough glue for about 5 profiles (!). The bottle is reasonably sized, but comes almost empty, only 3g of glue in there. Thats a scam IMO. I ended up using Bison Hard plastic glue, it worked almost as well, and one tube is enough for many tanks :).

I provided single models and platters with 44/88 pieces so you can print everything on 3 plates.

The tracks are slightly thicker, which impacts length. To get the tension right, I removed 1 link and added the 2mm "idler ring" sleeve over the idler wheel: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2227184/#files

description.text:
I was having issues printing the filament roll spool supplied by Febtops github.
I took their design and split it into 2 parts.
The way I've reproduced the part was as follows.

  1. Print the outer spool, don't use supports.
  2. Print the inner spool, Once the print reaches approx. 75mm in Z height, or 80% completion press the settings button then pause the print.
  3. In the print head movement window select 10 as the unit of measurement and raise the head 10 times.
  4. Slide the outer spool over the top of the inner spool then lower the print head 10 times again(i don't actually know if this is required or if the machine knows where to go back to).
  5. Then go back into the other menu and press play to continue the print.

This will reproduce the desired effect of having the outer spool free floating around the inner roller.
